> +	if (!p) {
> +		mutex_unlock(mutex);
> +		return NULL;
> +	}
> +	mutex_unlock(mutex);

All three mutex_unlock() sites (add failure, alloc_locked failure,
success) are correct; no double-unlock is possible.

When execmem_cache_add_locked() succeeds but __execmem_cache_alloc_locked()
returns NULL (maple tree OOM in mas_store_gfp), the block remains in
free_areas and is recoverable by the next caller -- correct behaviour.

The err_reset_direct_map label is only reachable before p is
overwritten by __execmem_cache_alloc_locked(), so vm and the original
vmalloc pointer are consistent there.

Both maple trees carry MT_FLAGS_LOCK_EXTERN tied to execmem_cache.mutex;
all callers of the _locked helpers now hold that mutex. The removal of
execmem_cache_add() is safe -- it had exactly one call site, which is
replaced by execmem_cache_add_locked() called directly under the mutex.

Fix looks correct to me.
